                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d345">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3953: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-25T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 25, 1934—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>314. Your 432, July 25, 2 p.m. Your telegram does not give the information
                    requested in the Department’s 301 of July 14, 3 p.m. You state “the British <hi
                        rend="italic">will</hi> stop immediately” et cetera. A full report is
                    desired in regard to the policy of the British Government up to the date of the
                    communication to the League of Nations to which you refer, especially in respect
                    to arms and munitions manufactured under contract for the Bolivian or Paraguayan
                    Governments and paid for in whole or in part before the embargo became
                    effective.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
